https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Unreasonable_Effectiveness_of_Mathematics_in_the_Natural_Sciences

Wigner was astonished that abstract mathematics, created purely by human thought with no concern for reality, so perfectly describes the physical universe. He called this fit “unreasonable” — meaning it seems too perfect to be explained by chance.

“The miracle of the appropriateness of the language of mathematics for the formulation of the laws of physics is a wonderful gift which we neither understand nor deserve.”

